<subSubSection id="22F009DB039B5BF0D4FB85DD9CBC1C15" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type locality">
<paragraph id="DB7EF084D8144F2CD334BB8299DAC8E9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="12A50E43219C80A92D4745B6FFB5D767" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Russia, Krasnodar krai, western Caucasus, Sochi River (20 km above Sochi; 800 m a.s.l.).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="130C4FE1CB471D7645BA314540FC384F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="159354C34DCE8E5EC1265845E9FB7E2E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1139543A8956AD42BD4D1135A5970A3F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Georgia, south-western Russia, Azerbaijan, Armenia, Turkey (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B80BE0EC875CEB7EE0DB75C6D97BC736" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Geographical (left) and vertical (right) distribution of Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471931" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</figureCitation>
). One of the most widespread species in the Caucasus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="716DE93BCA747B62873C64CFF737698D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="1A5786D723AD13E988528A35D65CC62C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="14508AE55FCCD3379FDD86D929C5518B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Larvae inhabit streams and rivers of various sizes, from larger braided low-altitude rivers to small streams at high altitude. Altitudinal range of sampling sites 6-2474 m a.s.l. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B43E376080B2199144E3C9C968A74296" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Geographical (left) and vertical (right) distribution of Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471931" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9</figureCitation>
). Most frequently found at low and middle altitude. Often syntopic with 
<taxonomicName id="725B41A5A19AF3C0D579CB545219260C" genus="E." lsidName="E. (C.) znojkoi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="znojkoi" subGenus="C.">E. (C.) znojkoi</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E69A6BC96F163242840335A4D350A9E3" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="main morphological diagnostics of larvae">
<paragraph id="480363FFABE7E01303B97D20B94A0BF8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Main morphological diagnostics of larvae.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6C92491D48DD5FC3E195154D97070E9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
(i) shape of head in male and female oval, trapezoidal (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EB6693ECD71BEE341994DCCB19086F06" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, G middle leg in dorsal view H, I abdominal terga J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471932" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10D, E</figureCitation>
); (ii) tergum X with well-developed postero-lateral projections (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F8B324BA3B356E2DBB551EECD2DB0E61" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) with detail of bristle-like seta B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K-M abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrow points on postero-lateral projection) N sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471933" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11K-M</figureCitation>
, arrows), sporadically poorly developed; (iii) abdominal sterna without coloration pattern (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="ECB678AAE8957A0D7AC443B5E8606638" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, G middle leg in dorsal view H, I abdominal terga J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471932" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10B, J</figureCitation>
); (iv) abdominal terga V-VII with triangular medial macula (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="76B36A1AADC8F376BB5FDDE704D83FF9" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, G middle leg in dorsal view H, I abdominal terga J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471932" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10H</figureCitation>
), sporadically poorly visible (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E02A43B3D11A99AB69446F3CB34CCA06" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, G middle leg in dorsal view H, I abdominal terga J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471932" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10I</figureCitation>
); (v) femora without medial hypodermal spot (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7482791D0716CC9B67823A7B5A0955E8" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A habitus in dorsal view B habitus in ventral view C habitus in lateral view D head of male in dorsal view E head of female in dorsal view F, G middle leg in dorsal view H, I abdominal terga J abdominal sterna II-VI K gills VII (in natural position from ventral view)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471932" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">10F, G</figureCitation>
); (vi) dorsal surface of labrum densely covered by bristle-like setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="99C40B839ED8A7CD1753221ED12F2478" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) with detail of bristle-like seta B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K-M abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrow points on postero-lateral projection) N sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471933" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11A</figureCitation>
); (v) setae on abdominal terga hair-like (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="67397B411A4F0DB68043E19BCA98A627" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) with detail of bristle-like seta B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K-M abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrow points on postero-lateral projection) N sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471933" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11E</figureCitation>
); (vi) gill plates III with well-developed projection (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8EFB2B754ACD1121ED5BE697079E7EAD" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Epeorus (Caucasiron) magnus, larva: A labrum (left half in dorsal view right half in ventral view) with detail of bristle-like seta B incisors of left mandible C incisors of right mandible D setae on dorsal surface of femora E surface and posterior margin of abdominal tergum VII F gill I G gill III H gill VII (flattened on slide) I, J gill VII (in natural position from ventral view) variability in shape K-M abdominal segments VIII-X in lateral view (arrow points on postero-lateral projection) N sternum IX of female with observed variability." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.986.56276.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/471933" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">11G</figureCitation>
); (vii) denticles along posterior margin of tergum VII strongly sclerotized, dense and curved (Fig. 
